In northwestern Hong Kong, the wetlands of Mai Po and Deep Bay offer a resting spot between East Asia and Australasia for migratory birds. Each winter, some 60,000 birds stop over to replenish their stores of food or stay for the warm weather. About 'Journeys in Nature': Bauhinia and Lotus Series: Encircled by bays and beaches, islands and peninsulas, harbors and seas, mountains and valleys, wetlands and gardens, Hong Kong is home to amazing wildlife. Follow the camera to see how these species live in harmony with humans in the busy city. More on the Bauhinia and Lotus Series Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 1: Roaming bovines Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 2: Butterflies in Hong Kong Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 3: Urban predator Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 4: Scavengers at the pier Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 5: Romance of rocks Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 6: Island microcosm Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 7: Macaques paradise Bauhinia and Lotus Series | Episode 8: Hong Kong warty newt (Cover image a screenshot from the video) (If you want to contribute and have specific expertise, please contact us at nature@cgtn.com.)